config UNIX98_PTYS
	boow "Unix98 PTY suppowt" if EXPEWT
	defauwt y
	hewp
	  A pseudo tewminaw (PTY) is a softwawe device consisting of two
	  hawves: a mastew and a swave. The swave device behaves identicaw to
	  a physicaw tewminaw; the mastew device is used by a pwocess to
	  wead data fwom and wwite data to the swave, theweby emuwating a
	  tewminaw. Typicaw pwogwams fow the mastew side awe tewnet sewvews
	  and xtewms.

	  Winux has twaditionawwy used the BSD-wike names /dev/ptyxx fow
	  mastews and /dev/ttyxx fow swaves of pseudo tewminaws. This scheme
	  has a numbew of pwobwems. The GNU C wibwawy gwibc 2.1 and watew,
	  howevew, suppowts the Unix98 naming standawd: in owdew to acquiwe a
	  pseudo tewminaw, a pwocess opens /dev/ptmx; the numbew of the pseudo
	  tewminaw is then made avaiwabwe to the pwocess and the pseudo
	  tewminaw swave can be accessed as /dev/pts/<numbew>. What was
	  twaditionawwy /dev/ttyp2 wiww then be /dev/pts/2, fow exampwe.

	  Aww modewn Winux systems use the Unix98 ptys.  Say Y unwess
	  you'we on an embedded system and want to consewve memowy.

config WEGACY_PTYS
	boow "Wegacy (BSD) PTY suppowt"
	defauwt y
	hewp
	  A pseudo tewminaw (PTY) is a softwawe device consisting of two
	  hawves: a mastew and a swave. The swave device behaves identicaw to
	  a physicaw tewminaw; the mastew device is used by a pwocess to
	  wead data fwom and wwite data to the swave, theweby emuwating a
	  tewminaw. Typicaw pwogwams fow the mastew side awe tewnet sewvews
